        <title type="text">Question page: when am I reading a different answer?</title>
            <category scheme="https://meta.stackoverflow.com/tags" term="feature-request" />
            <category scheme="https://meta.stackoverflow.com/tags" term="status-review" />
            <category scheme="https://meta.stackoverflow.com/tags" term="redesign-2026" />
        <author>
            <name>David</name>
            <uri>https://meta.stackoverflow.com/users/15016042</uri>
        </author>
        <link rel="alternate" href="https://meta.stackoverflow.com/questions/438307/question-page-when-am-i-reading-a-different-answer" />
        <published>2026-02-25T20:08:48Z</published>
        <updated>2026-02-25T23:26:58Z</updated>
        <summary type="html">
            &lt;p&gt;I keep overlooking the difference between one answer and the next, and even between the question and its first answer. This isn&#x27;t surprising, given the decreased horizontal movement (e.g, indentation), font sizes, and background shades of the new design. To digest a question and its answers now requires more attention because critical context changes are harder to spot. It&#x27;s particularly egregious when the comment thread line appears to &amp;quot;point&amp;quot; to the following answer, which has no comments but is followed by a third answer. The comment thread &lt;em&gt;actually&lt;/em&gt; has no relationship to the second answer, and the third answer &lt;em&gt;isn&#x27;t&lt;/em&gt; (usually) a reply to the second answer.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Could the start of a new answer be more clearly marked (e.g, with more than one line of white space, a line, or a prominent UI element)?&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;
        </summary>
    </entry>
