        <re:rank scheme="https://meta.stackoverflow.com">60</re:rank>
        <title type="text">I tried the redesign beta and the experience was awful</title>
            <category scheme="https://meta.stackoverflow.com/tags" term="discussion" />
            <category scheme="https://meta.stackoverflow.com/tags" term="user-interface" />
            <category scheme="https://meta.stackoverflow.com/tags" term="user-experience" />
            <category scheme="https://meta.stackoverflow.com/tags" term="redesign-2026" />
        <author>
            <name>Thomas Owens</name>
            <uri>https://meta.stackoverflow.com/users/572</uri>
        </author>
        <link rel="alternate" href="https://meta.stackoverflow.com/questions/438297/i-tried-the-redesign-beta-and-the-experience-was-awful" />
        <published>2026-02-25T14:51:04Z</published>
        <updated>2026-02-25T20:39:52Z</updated>
        <summary type="html">
            &lt;p&gt;Right from the homepage, &amp;quot;AI Assist&amp;quot; is staring me in the face. When I go to Stack Overflow, I don&#x27;t want to necessarily start a chat with anyone. If I wanted to have a chat, I&#x27;d use Copilot (or similar) in my editor or IDE or open Gemini (or similar) in my browser, depending on the context. That doesn&#x27;t necessarily mean AI doesn&#x27;t have a place in content discovery. I can imagine several ways that AI can enhance search, from trying alternative search terms to something more like &lt;a href=&quot;https://blog.google/products-and-platforms/products/search/web-guide-labs/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer&quot;&gt;Google&#x27;s Web Guide&lt;/a&gt;. But a chat isn&#x27;t what I want at all. It pushes search to the upper right and &amp;quot;interesting posts&amp;quot; down the page, taking the two primary things I may want to do out of focus.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The left sidebar is interesting.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Organizing different types of content is useful. Personally, I&#x27;m open to alternative types of content on Stack Overflow and across the broader network. I&#x27;d like to see what can be done to enhance more open-ended discussions, collaborative wiki articles, or individually owned blog posts, in addition to the traditional/strict Q&amp;amp;A format.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;However, the order is a bit strange. I don&#x27;t know what the purpose of &amp;quot;Companies&amp;quot; is. Putting Questions. Putting Tags up so high is a bit weird, since there&#x27;s not much useful stuff you can do on the page it links to. I&#x27;d probably move Chat just below Questions, then put Tags. Blog is also weird, but that&#x27;s because I think the Blog doesn&#x27;t know what it&#x27;s supposed to be - is it a marketing blog, a technical interest blog curated by the company, a bit of both? It&#x27;s not the same kind of user-generated content as the other types of Content, though, so it is a bit out of place. Putting Collectives in the Communities section instead of the Content section is also a bit weird, since Collectives relate to the user-generated content on the site I&#x27;m on rather than content from outside sites.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In the iconography, the icons for All Communities and the header icon for company type things are the same. That&#x27;s confusing since they are two separate concepts.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Putting the Resources so far down the list is rough. It hides a lot of useful content. I&#x27;d move Help and Meta up to where Home and AI Assist are now. I&#x27;d move Users to the Content section, probably toward the bottom. On SO (and only SO), I&#x27;d also probably put Jobs in the Content section, especially since Companies are there. Saves need a place. Maybe in the top bar, though, next to the notifications, awards, and profile?&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Moving into the list of questions under &amp;quot;Interesting posts for you&amp;quot;, I find the structure of the question lists confusing. The most important parts are the title and body preview, but they appear below the metadata. I find myself getting confused. For the person listed, it&#x27;s not initially clear who they are. Are they the asker? The last answerer or editor? It looks like they are the asker. My question here is...why do I care about the person in this view? This is especially true when the last change is attributed to Community. I&#x27;d move the view counter below the votes and answer counters, remove the person&#x27;s name and reputation from this view, and place the last content change information next to the tags.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;When viewing mixed content, it should be more apparent what the content is. The difference between a Q&amp;amp;A and a discussion question isn&#x27;t that obvious from the home page view. There is the tag (e.g., &amp;quot;best practices&amp;quot;), but that&#x27;s not different enough. Some kind of more apparent visual distinction is key, and if more content types are added, it would be even more important since the view you end up on is different for these different content types.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Clicking through to a question, it starts off OK.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I would swap the title and metadata. I&#x27;d put the asker attribution, ask date, and edit date next to the tags. I&#x27;d also explicitly add who the last editor was, even if it is the author. I would move the views to a different location, next to the votes.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Putting the vote at the bottom is interesting. At first, I didn&#x27;t like it. But it does make it harder to vote without reading the question, which is probably a good behavior change. I&#x27;d move the view information next to the votes. I&#x27;d also make the separation between the question and the answers more prominent. The text for &amp;quot;2 Answers&amp;quot; isn&#x27;t that different than the text for headers in the question.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Removing question comments is a bad idea, especially without an alternative. Comments have two purposes when attached to questions. One is to identify potential issues or problems that prevent giving a good answer. The other is to provide tagential information that may be helpful in curation, such as identifying related questions (esp. on other network sites). There&#x27;s no way to do this kind of thing now, and that hurts. This would be unacceptable on other sites in the network and would be a huge show-stopper.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The distinction between answers and answer comments could also be bigger. Yes, they are indented, but it&#x27;s not obvious enough when quickly scrolling. Better separation between answers could help, too. I&#x27;m not sure if there would need to be changes to both the comments and answers, but scrolling through makes it hard to see where one answer ends, comments begin, and the next answer begins. The share for comments should be removed as they are transient for Q&amp;amp;A. I&#x27;d also remove nested comments in Q&amp;amp;A. Again, Q&amp;amp;A needs to be about the question and strict answers. Exploring other content formats could be useful, but doesn&#x27;t need to influence Q&amp;amp;A as much.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I&#x27;ve left similar feedback before, but the question type needs to be rethought. I&#x27;m not opposed to the idea of &amp;quot;Q&amp;amp;A&amp;quot;, &amp;quot;Discussion&amp;quot;, and other content types. But &amp;quot;tooling recommendation&amp;quot; steps all over the &lt;a href=&quot;https://softwarerecs.stackexchange.com/&quot;&gt;Software Recommendations&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://hardwarerecs.stackexchange.com/&quot;&gt;Hardware Recommendation&lt;/a&gt; communities, each of which have developed strong guidelines for high quality content in their respective domains. &amp;quot;Best practice&amp;quot; doesn&#x27;t acknowledge that &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cynefin_framework&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer&quot;&gt;the complexity of software development&lt;/a&gt; forces it into a situation where there are context-sensitive good practices instead of best practices, as well as starting to step on the toes of &lt;a href=&quot;https://softwareengineering.stackexchange.com/&quot;&gt;Software Engineering&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;
        </summary>
    </entry>
